com.vmware.vcenter.vm.hardware.adapter

Interface Sata

  • All Superinterfaces:
    com.vmware.vapi.internal.bindings.CompletionStageService, SataTypes, Service
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    SataStub

    public interface Sata
extends Service, SataTypes, com.vmware.vapi.internal.bindings.CompletionStageService
    The Sata interface provides methods for configuring the virtual SATA adapters of a virtual machine.

      • create

        Sata.CreateInvocation create(java.lang.String vm,
                             SataTypes.CreateSpec spec)
        Adds a virtual SATA adapter to the virtual machine.

        Invocation Result:
        Virtual SATA adapter identifier. The return value will be an identifier for the resource type: com.vmware.vcenter.vm.hardware.SataAdapter.

        Parameters:
        vm - Virtual machine identifier. The parameter must be an identifier for the resource type: VirtualMachine.
        spec - Specification for the new virtual SATA adapter.
        Returns:
        instance of Sata.CreateInvocation which upon invoke executes the above described create operation. The operation result or the operation error will be stored in the CompletionStageFuture that invoke returns.
        Throws:
        Error - if the system reports an error while responding to the request.
        Error - if the system reported that the SATA adapter was created but was unable to confirm the creation because the identifier of the new adapter could not be determined.
        NotAllowedInCurrentState - if the virtual machine is suspended
        NotFound - if the virtual machine is not found.
        UnableToAllocateResource - if there are no more available SATA buses on the virtual machine.
        ResourceInUse - if the specified SATA bus or PCI address is in use.
        InvalidArgument - if the specified SATA bus or PCI address is out of bounds.
        ResourceBusy - if the virtual machine is busy performing another operation.
        ResourceInaccessible - if the virtual machine's configuration state cannot be accessed.
        ServiceUnavailable - if the system is unable to communicate with a service to complete the request.
        Unauthenticated - if the user can not be authenticated.
        Unauthorized - if the user doesn't have the required privileges.
        Unsupported - if the guest operating system of the virtual machine is not supported and spec includes null properties that default to guest-specific values.
